WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.080
Good morning, and welcome back to RStudioConf.

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:22.600
It's really great to see you all here again, whether it's in person or on one of our livestreams.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:27.559
But now it's my very great honor to introduce our next keynote speaker, my colleague and

00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:36.959
friend Jenny Bryan.

00:00:36.959 --> 00:00:40.959
Jenny's work has almost certainly touched you in some way, whether it's one of her books

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:46.439
like Happy Git With R or What They Forgot To Teach You, or perhaps it's because you're

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:53.119
afraid that she'll set your computer on fire because you use setwd.

00:00:53.119 --> 00:00:58.200
Or maybe you're using one of her packages like Read Excel or Google Sheets to get data

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:03.000
out of spreadsheets, whether it's Excel or Google and into R.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.120
But of all the packages, of all the work that Jenny has done, I think my favorite package

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:11.959
is the reprex package.

00:01:11.959 --> 00:01:18.720
Not only because it's such a great tool to help you get help from other people, but I

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:24.360
think it's one of the rare packages that has, like, no precedent in any other package.

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:25.879
It's in any other programming language.

00:01:25.879 --> 00:01:28.279
It's something that's genuinely new.

00:01:28.279 --> 00:01:34.080
So without further ado, I'd like to welcome Jenny Bryan.

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:52.559
So this, I think, is R's most infamous error message.

00:01:52.559 --> 00:01:54.639
Objective type closure is not subsettable.

00:01:54.639 --> 00:01:58.480
It was my title as a joke for a while, and then people thought I should actually stick

00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:00.080
with it.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:06.320
So I have 20 years of experience triggering this bug, which is why I can now do it in

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:08.279
two lines of code.

00:02:08.279 --> 00:02:11.720
And this is also, I think, commonly how it actually happens, although it's usually never

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:14.039
quite this clear.

00:02:14.039 --> 00:02:19.759
But you create your main data object, you call it dat, then you promptly lose all memory

00:02:19.759 --> 00:02:28.559
of having done so, and you ask for the X column of DF, which you haven't made, but DF exists.

00:02:28.559 --> 00:02:32.520
It's a function that gives you the density of the F distribution.

00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:38.639
So what you've asked for makes no sense, and R tells you this in this very special way.

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:45.720
And my sort of fantasy message down there is maybe it would be able to somehow read

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:49.240
my mind, which is obviously not going to happen.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:53.839
And so this sets the mood for the next hour, where I want to talk about general strategies

00:02:53.839 --> 00:02:58.520
for coping with confusing and frustrating situations.

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:02.600
So you went into data science, you were probably told that it's going to be glamour and fun

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:10.880
like 24-7, and you make very creative concoctions that you present, and people love to consume

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:12.240
it.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:18.039
But there's all this drudgery, as there is in any job, where we actually spend a much

00:03:18.039 --> 00:03:22.600
greater proportion of our time and our mental energy.

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:28.279
And so I've sort of made a habit of talking and teaching about those things so that you

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:33.800
feel really cool and have fun, but you get your drudgery done as well.

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:38.240
So we're not using Slido for live questions, although you're welcome to ask them, because

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:45.839
I'm going to blog about this talk later, but I am using Slido live for some polls.

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:52.000
So if you're willing to get your laptop or your phone out, I'm curious what your current

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.240
main debugging method is, and if you use multiple, as you probably do, you will have to pick

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:58.300
a favorite.

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:01.759
And while I'm letting you take this poll, I'm going to say a few more words about why

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:06.860
I think this is so important, the drudgery part.

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:11.119
So if we don't give a name to these things and give them dignity, when you lose half

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:16.519
your day to doing something like this, it's extremely demotivating, because you feel like

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:20.100
you haven't actually gotten any real work done.

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:25.600
And the other risk, especially with debugging, is if you're only reactive and you're always

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:31.839
dealing with today's bug, it means that you are constantly putting out fires and you don't

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:38.040
probably have the time at that point to develop your debugging skills and be a little bit

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:39.559
proactive about it.

00:04:39.559 --> 00:04:42.839
But you shouldn't be perpetually surprised that there's a new bug.

00:04:42.839 --> 00:04:43.839
Like really?

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:44.839
Again?

00:04:44.839 --> 00:04:45.839
Today?

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:49.760
This is going to happen every day, and it's actually worth giving some thought to how

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:51.820
you want to do things.

00:04:51.820 --> 00:05:01.779
So let's see if anyone's responded.

00:05:01.779 --> 00:05:10.700
I think they have, but it's difficult for me to refresh over here.

00:05:10.700 --> 00:05:14.619
It's a very complicated problem with how I'm using this computer.

00:05:14.619 --> 00:05:22.839
So I am going to keep taking polls, and I am not going to show you the results.

00:05:22.839 --> 00:05:26.980
And I will assume they are what I think they should be, which is that it's probably all

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:27.980
over the map there.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:33.140
I will reveal this in the promised blog post as well.

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:34.339
So here's where we're going to go.

00:05:34.339 --> 00:05:39.980
There's four sections of this talk, and I hope that there's something for everyone here,

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:44.980
depending on, like, your R experience can be quite little or quite a lot, and that there

00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:49.179
will be something that you find interesting, useful, or at least makes you feel very validated

00:05:49.179 --> 00:05:50.980
in what you do.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:54.899
And this is also basically approximately the order in which I do these things.

00:05:54.899 --> 00:05:59.940
And they do all come up all the time on most puzzling situations.

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:05.299
So the first thing I want to talk about is the beauty of resetting things.

00:06:05.299 --> 00:06:08.100
Earlier this week we ran a ton of workshops.

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:09.380
I helped out in one.

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:16.059
I was not in charge because I was doing this, and this reaffirmed my commitment to how important

00:06:16.059 --> 00:06:21.420
the idea of resets is and why it really should be your first strategy.

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:26.140
So as soon as you get some sort of error, I don't know about you, but I immediately

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:29.619
I just send that same command again.

00:06:29.619 --> 00:06:34.380
Because maybe it's going to work this time.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:38.260
And it does not ever, ever work.

00:06:38.260 --> 00:06:44.380
But there is a small variation on this that is an extremely productive implementation,

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:51.380
and it's the world's most famous troubleshooting advice for anything, but especially tech,

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:56.100
because it's so hard to get this right, that you should try turning it off and turning

00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:58.100
it back on again.

00:06:58.100 --> 00:06:59.100
And why is that?

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:04.140
So this is a super corny phrase that we have all heard before, that if you love something,

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:08.339
you need to set it free, and if it's really yours, it will come back.

00:07:08.339 --> 00:07:12.179
And I think this applies to unloved things as well.

00:07:12.179 --> 00:07:19.459
So if you have a strange problem, and it just actually doesn't make much sense, consider

00:07:19.459 --> 00:07:24.260
setting it free, restarting R, and see if it comes back.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:25.260
Okay?

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:29.160
So I want you to restart R often, and especially when things get weird.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:33.739
And you might think I'm being glib or I'm just trying to sweep some problem under the

00:07:33.739 --> 00:07:36.100
rug, but that is not actually true.

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:42.140
One of the things that's pretty unusual about R is we install and update packages from R,

00:07:42.140 --> 00:07:46.700
and this is a little bit like working on your airplane engine while you're flying.

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:52.899
And I think people updating and installing packages while they're doing work in R, and

00:07:52.899 --> 00:07:57.820
especially if they have multiple R sessions open, is a common reason why things get funky

00:07:57.820 --> 00:08:03.220
in a way that's quite difficult to debug and understand, and the good news is you don't

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:11.660
have to quit, restart, and you're guaranteed to have the package version that's loaded

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:14.700
into memory view, the one that was installed on disk.

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:20.399
So that's an example of why this is a legitimate way to reset things.

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:22.679
So how do we actually do this in R?

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:25.579
So this is the R studio version.

00:08:25.579 --> 00:08:32.179
There is a menu entry where you can restart R. I have this keyboard shortcut emblazoned

00:08:32.179 --> 00:08:33.539
into my brain.

00:08:33.539 --> 00:08:36.820
It's something I do many times per day.

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:40.460
And the second thing I recommend that you consider, this is kind of a big lifestyle

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:49.979
change, so don't do it right now, is to consider not reloading your workspace at startup and

00:08:49.979 --> 00:08:57.539
not saving your workspace when you quit R. It's a pretty radical lifestyle change.

00:08:57.539 --> 00:08:58.539
Yes.

00:08:58.539 --> 00:09:03.659
And I get a lot of pushback on this, so I do appreciate the clapping.

00:09:03.659 --> 00:09:07.299
I'm going to remember that when I get this week's pushback.

00:09:07.299 --> 00:09:11.460
This is the way to do this if you were just starting R in a terminal, and I also just

00:09:11.460 --> 00:09:15.200
want to use this as a proxy for that figure I just showed you.

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:22.820
So you can start R with command line flags, including no save and no restore data.

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:26.500
And I want to argue this is vastly superior to another thing that a lot of us do, and

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:34.700
I have lots of this on my computer from previous years, where people use RM list equals LS.

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:39.500
So that lists all the objects in the global workspace, and it deletes them.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:44.140
And so this is a really common command to see at the top of R scripts, and believe me,

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:48.619
this was my 100% practice all the time.

00:09:48.619 --> 00:09:52.140
But the problem is it doesn't really go far enough.

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:55.580
So this brings me to my next poll, and I'm going to continue to believe that you're all

00:09:55.580 --> 00:10:03.659
filling out the poll, and I want you to think about these six R commands, and they all have

00:10:03.659 --> 00:10:05.859
some sort of effect.

00:10:05.859 --> 00:10:11.140
And then let's say you execute this command, RM list equals LS.

00:10:11.140 --> 00:10:16.900
Which of these effects will persist in the session after that?

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:22.500
And I will give you a minute to do this, because this one requires a bit more thinking.

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:40.340
You should be selecting multiple answers.

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:42.640
And I didn't give you permission, but you are allowed to talk to your neighbor, which

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:44.960
many of you clearly are.

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:46.460
We encourage that.

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:49.460
It's not cheating.

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:23.179
Are they good?

00:11:23.179 --> 00:11:25.140
Okay.

00:11:25.140 --> 00:11:27.780
I hear there are responses.

00:11:27.780 --> 00:11:31.419
So I'm going to do the big reveal.

00:11:31.419 --> 00:11:37.500
So library dplyr leaves dplyr attached.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:43.500
So that persists after RM list equals LS.

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:45.919
Redefining the summary function, that's been cleared.

00:11:45.919 --> 00:11:50.000
So you have a reset summary to its normal definition.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:55.359
If you've changed an option, like strings as factors from true to false, that persists

00:11:55.359 --> 00:11:56.679
in the session.

00:11:56.679 --> 00:12:00.799
If you've changed the language of the session that's going to affect what error messages

00:12:00.799 --> 00:12:04.880
look like, for example, that persists.

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:08.039
Binding 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 to the name X, that's gone.

00:12:08.039 --> 00:12:09.400
X is gone.

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:13.200
But if you've attached an environment or a data frame to the search path, that's still

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:15.039
there as well.

00:12:15.039 --> 00:12:21.520
And so all of those four things that persist here aren't top of mind.

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:23.559
You're really thinking about those objects.

00:12:23.559 --> 00:12:28.280
But they all have an effect on how your subsequent code runs.

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:33.880
And so this makes it very easy to develop code under a set of expectations that will

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:40.919
not hold when someone else runs that code or when you are running it in a fresh R session.

00:12:40.919 --> 00:12:47.260
So it's for that reason that I think starting R in a way where you don't reload the workspace

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:50.559
and you don't save it is vastly superior to this practice.

00:12:50.559 --> 00:12:56.520
Because it's really, like, if you care enough to kill your workspace, you care enough to

00:12:56.520 --> 00:13:00.200
restart R. You should go that far.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:04.159
So fresh starts, clean the workspace, reset options and environment variables and clear

00:13:04.159 --> 00:13:06.000
the search path.

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:10.239
So I want us to think of this as your R sessions are like crops.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:11.239
You grow them.

00:13:11.239 --> 00:13:14.080
You harvest them without any fear.

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:16.239
Not a house plant.

00:13:16.239 --> 00:13:20.960
There's another saying from the cloud and VM world that's more morbid about livestock

00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:21.960
and pets.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:27.460
So this is our slightly kinder, gentler version of that.

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:35.679
And this practice of kind of having no memory in some sense of not loading a workspace and

00:13:35.679 --> 00:13:39.840
not saving it is pretty difficult to implement by itself.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:44.039
It really works best in synergy with some other habits.

00:13:44.039 --> 00:13:48.780
In particular, saving your source is obviously very important.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:53.039
So source is real and there's some other habits that are quite important.

00:13:53.039 --> 00:13:54.760
So at the beginning I actually should have mentioned this.

00:13:54.760 --> 00:14:01.979
There's an Rstd.io debugging short link and that will take you to a readme on GitHub that

00:14:01.979 --> 00:14:07.340
has a lot of links related to the talks that aren't in the slides, but if you want to follow

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:10.260
up on some of these ideas.

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:11.260
So let's talk about reprex.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:15.460
I'm very excited that Hadley likes it.

00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:17.619
And I should really well, we'll get to this.

00:14:17.619 --> 00:14:18.619
Credit.

00:14:18.619 --> 00:14:21.820
It's really a wrapper around things other people have made, but it's a very handy wrapper,

00:14:21.820 --> 00:14:23.320
I will have to say.

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:27.340
And I'm kind of talking about the package, but I really want to talk about the reprex

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:30.419
mindset more than anything.

00:14:30.419 --> 00:14:34.700
So you know that if I get a mistake, the first thing I do is I submit the same command

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:35.700
again.

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:42.179
The next thing you might do is sort of brood, dither, and fret about what you've just seen.

00:14:42.179 --> 00:14:47.219
And a lot of people just immediately go into speculating, usually about worst case scenarios,

00:14:47.219 --> 00:14:49.780
about what could possibly be wrong.

00:14:49.780 --> 00:14:54.460
And this is just as effective as submitting the same command again, which is to say that

00:14:54.460 --> 00:14:57.340
it is not effective in the least.

00:14:57.340 --> 00:15:06.020
And so one good way to knock yourself out of this paralysis is to work a small example.

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:10.979
And for years, I was a statistics professor who cared about R, but I was by no means a

00:15:10.979 --> 00:15:13.900
professional R programmer.

00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:17.659
And then over various years, I started hanging out more and more with the experts, and I

00:15:17.659 --> 00:15:20.700
think I've probably crossed the line into being one of those experts now.

00:15:20.700 --> 00:15:21.940
And here's one of the things I learned.

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:27.820
I used to think that the experts just knew everything all the time.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:29.700
And that's not true.

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:31.619
They know some things for sure.

00:15:31.619 --> 00:15:37.340
But a bigger distinction is they have this habit of working an example.

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:44.859
So if there's a really weird situation, they test a theory or they gather some data.

00:15:44.859 --> 00:15:50.059
And this is much more approachable as a strategy than trying to solve all your problems.

00:15:50.059 --> 00:15:55.979
All you have to do is work one small example that sheds a new light on the problem, confirms

00:15:55.979 --> 00:16:01.099
so-and-so's theory or rules so-and-so's theory out.

00:16:01.099 --> 00:16:04.940
So the term minimum reproducible example is preexisting.

00:16:04.940 --> 00:16:09.799
It's important across all programming languages, and a minimum reproducible example is much

00:16:09.799 --> 00:16:16.460
beloved in places like Stack Overflow and GitHub, and my colleague decided to coin the

00:16:16.460 --> 00:16:19.979
term reprex by mushing those two words together.

00:16:19.979 --> 00:16:26.619
And at that same time, I was creating this package mostly out of wild frustration with

00:16:26.619 --> 00:16:30.580
code conversations with my students, so I used the name.

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:35.140
And making a reprex is both a science and an art.

00:16:35.140 --> 00:16:41.780
So the reproducible part is the science part, and that means you've provided code that someone

00:16:41.780 --> 00:16:43.979
else could actually run.

00:16:43.979 --> 00:16:47.099
And that's what the reprex package can help with.

00:16:47.099 --> 00:16:52.179
It can only help with sort of mechanical, robotic things.

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:56.580
But then there's this whole aspect about the art of making a reprex, and that's making

00:16:56.580 --> 00:16:58.739
it minimal.

00:16:58.739 --> 00:17:01.280
And only humans, really, can do that.

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:05.599
And so that comes with having more and more experience, and if you can't instantly give

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:12.339
yourself more experience, you can hang out in places where you're exposed to good reprexes

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:17.939
all the time, and you'll start to absorb what the principles of that are.

00:17:17.939 --> 00:17:24.060
So I'm about to show you a few tiny snippets of code that aren't quite complete and that

00:17:24.060 --> 00:17:31.739
recapitulate a lot of the struggles seen when people post examples, and then we'll see a

00:17:31.739 --> 00:17:34.420
nice, beautiful reprex.

00:17:34.420 --> 00:17:41.500
So I want you to sort of run this code in your mind and identify what the mistake is.

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:43.219
Like, why is there an error?

00:17:43.219 --> 00:17:46.180
And I'll give you a couple seconds to look at this.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:54.260
So template is a string.

00:17:54.260 --> 00:17:59.300
It's got placeholders for an exclamation and an adjective.

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:02.219
And then I call a function praise on it.

00:18:02.219 --> 00:18:07.260
But this is not a function in base R, so the error that we get is that it can't find the

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:08.579
function praise.

00:18:08.579 --> 00:18:12.140
So this is a problem that you see when people post a lot of code, but they don't tell you

00:18:12.140 --> 00:18:16.060
which packages they're using, and you get to slowly sort of figure that out through

00:18:16.060 --> 00:18:18.020
20 questions.

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:20.900
So here's another small variant of this.

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.260
Let's run that again in your head.

00:18:23.260 --> 00:18:30.660
Imagine it in a fresh R session, not the one that we just used.

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:36.579
So here we do remember to attach the praise package, and then we call praise on template.

00:18:36.939 --> 00:18:39.859
Template has not been defined here.

00:18:39.859 --> 00:18:44.780
It might exist on someone's computer, whoever ran that code.

00:18:44.780 --> 00:18:48.900
But in terms of by the time this code goes somewhere, again, someone won't be able to

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:50.739
run this.

00:18:50.739 --> 00:18:56.619
So in this super tiny example, this is what a complete RevRex would look like.

00:18:56.619 --> 00:18:58.540
We declare all of our dependencies.

00:18:58.540 --> 00:19:00.540
We are attaching the praise package.

00:19:00.540 --> 00:19:05.099
We create all of our inputs, like this template object.

00:19:05.099 --> 00:19:09.020
And then we do the thing we've come to do, which is to emit some praise.

00:19:09.020 --> 00:19:16.859
And so making this type of error and correction easier is one of the main reasons for the

00:19:16.859 --> 00:19:21.660
RevRex package is to sort of help people put their code on a little spaceship and send

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:25.459
it somewhere to be executed in isolation.

00:19:25.459 --> 00:19:29.939
And so the reproducible part is that there's no reliance on hidden state or secret things

00:19:29.939 --> 00:19:33.900
that I know that you don't know or that are true about my R session that aren't true about

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:36.619
yours.

00:19:36.619 --> 00:19:43.140
And another reason it's incredibly important to provide to express your problem in runnable

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:45.939
code is because of this.

00:19:45.939 --> 00:19:51.060
So I don't know if you've ever tried to, like, help a relative with a tech problem over the

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:52.900
phone.

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:55.339
But there's what someone thinks they're doing.

00:19:55.339 --> 00:19:58.180
I trust, like, everyone has good intentions.

00:19:58.180 --> 00:20:00.260
And what they say they're doing.

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:02.979
And then there's what they're actually doing.

00:20:03.060 --> 00:20:09.660
And quite often this gap between these two things, like, that's where the problem is.

00:20:09.660 --> 00:20:14.579
And so if all you're getting is what you think and say you're doing, it's incredibly hard

00:20:14.579 --> 00:20:17.619
for someone else to maybe help you troubleshoot things.

00:20:17.619 --> 00:20:24.819
So by providing your minimum reproducible examples as runnable code, you get rid of

00:20:24.819 --> 00:20:30.939
all sorts of opinions people have about what's wrong, potential for vocabulary confusion

00:20:30.939 --> 00:20:36.900
where you say potato, I say potatoes, and it's much easier to figure out what's going

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:37.900
on.

00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:42.739
So to turn back to minimal.

00:20:42.739 --> 00:20:46.939
When you're trying to figure out what's going on in a confusing situation, you can think

00:20:46.939 --> 00:20:52.060
of it as the classic looking for a needle in a haystack exercise.

00:20:52.060 --> 00:20:56.739
And so common sense would tell you that if you can make that haystack smaller, it's going

00:20:56.739 --> 00:20:58.900
to be a lot easier to find your needle.

00:20:58.900 --> 00:21:04.099
And this is the basic principle behind why making a reprex minimal is so important.

00:21:04.099 --> 00:21:10.339
So your goal is to try to make the code and the data as small and simple as possible.

00:21:10.339 --> 00:21:15.300
And if you took anything else away, it wouldn't be making your point or it wouldn't show the

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:16.300
error.

00:21:16.300 --> 00:21:21.020
So I'm going to show a wild caught problem.

00:21:21.020 --> 00:21:27.099
And this was kindly donated by Brooke Matabonwu with her permission.

00:21:27.099 --> 00:21:31.819
And so this was a problem she shared with me privately at first.

00:21:31.819 --> 00:21:34.260
And it's okay if you can't see all of this code.

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:40.859
It's kind of the point, the meta point of this slide is that wild caught puzzles are

00:21:40.859 --> 00:21:42.459
complicated.

00:21:42.459 --> 00:21:47.459
And so the main thing you want to know here is that this is a little data ingest snippet.

00:21:47.459 --> 00:21:53.380
It brings in a bunch of Excel worksheets that come from a bunch of Excel workbooks, brings

00:21:53.380 --> 00:21:58.140
everything in as a list of many, many, many data frames, and then turns all the variables

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:00.300
into character.

00:22:00.300 --> 00:22:04.699
And then out at the bottom pops this completely mysterious message error.

00:22:04.699 --> 00:22:07.140
The dot, dot, dot list does not contain three elements.

00:22:07.140 --> 00:22:12.939
So it's not at all clear where in the pipeline that's coming from or what she can actually

00:22:12.939 --> 00:22:15.079
do about it.

00:22:15.079 --> 00:22:18.300
And the thing I want to show here, and this was a legitimate problem that needed to be

00:22:18.300 --> 00:22:25.459
solved, but this is like a wild caught example by definition probably uses private files

00:22:25.459 --> 00:22:27.180
that only you have.

00:22:27.180 --> 00:22:30.780
In this case, you know, she needs ten lines of code to do what she's doing.

00:22:30.780 --> 00:22:34.060
That's just the complexity of what she's doing.

00:22:34.060 --> 00:22:37.459
Eight functions from five different add-on packages.

00:22:37.459 --> 00:22:41.719
So we chat a little and Brooke also goes off and sort of ruthlessly minimizes things and

00:22:41.719 --> 00:22:45.619
eventually this surfaces as an issue on dplyr.

00:22:45.619 --> 00:22:52.260
And by the time she was done, this is what the reprex looked like that enabled a coherent

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:56.459
conversation to happen, and it was really more about things were happening in various

00:22:56.459 --> 00:23:00.180
packages and we gradually got a much better error message here.

00:23:00.180 --> 00:23:03.819
But the key features are that we have inlined data.

00:23:03.819 --> 00:23:06.219
She defines the data frame there.

00:23:06.219 --> 00:23:07.979
And she calls one function.

00:23:07.979 --> 00:23:10.780
So inline data, not private data.

00:23:10.780 --> 00:23:12.660
Two lines of code, not ten.

00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:16.660
It involves one package, not five, one function, not eight.

00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:19.660
And this gets to the heart of the matter much quickly.

00:23:19.660 --> 00:23:21.339
So how do you actually do this?

00:23:21.339 --> 00:23:26.859
And I would say one of the easiest places to start is simplifying the data.

00:23:26.859 --> 00:23:35.380
So if the data that created your problem has 500 rows, why can't it have 499?

00:23:35.380 --> 00:23:36.380
Why not 498?

00:23:36.380 --> 00:23:42.260
And, like, keep making it smaller and you will gradually reveal to yourself which features

00:23:42.260 --> 00:23:47.140
of that data frame are important for showing the problem.

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:50.099
So minimal reprex has small, simple inputs.

00:23:50.099 --> 00:23:52.540
It's awesome if you can inline them.

00:23:52.540 --> 00:23:57.260
And no calls to packages or functions that aren't actually needed.

00:23:57.260 --> 00:24:01.619
I watch a lot of the repositories for our packages on GitHub, and there's a certain

00:24:01.619 --> 00:24:07.579
type of notification or actually it's usually, like, 100 notifications I get at once when

00:24:07.579 --> 00:24:10.739
Hadley does issue triage.

00:24:10.739 --> 00:24:16.339
And so one of the things he will do is he'll post, and he always says it this way, slightly

00:24:16.339 --> 00:24:19.020
more minimal reprex.

00:24:19.020 --> 00:24:25.060
So I actually did a GitHub search for that phrase and went and looked at these issue

00:24:25.060 --> 00:24:26.099
threads.

00:24:26.099 --> 00:24:30.060
And this is a sketchy diagram because I like the way that looks, but this is actually based

00:24:30.060 --> 00:24:32.819
on data and a ggplot2 figure.

00:24:32.819 --> 00:24:39.459
And I counted the lines of code in Hadley's version versus the original version.

00:24:39.459 --> 00:24:41.619
And they're consistently a lot smaller.

00:24:41.619 --> 00:24:47.180
And this is lines of code, but this would apply to many measures of reprex size, whatever

00:24:47.180 --> 00:24:49.060
that might mean.

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:51.939
And you might say, well, Jenny, that's great.

00:24:51.939 --> 00:24:57.260
Hadley has special knowledge of these packages and is maybe better at this than I am.

00:24:57.260 --> 00:25:03.099
And that is possibly true, but I think there's something else going on that makes me want

00:25:03.099 --> 00:25:07.500
to still point out how important this is.

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:10.500
And there are a lot of reasons to make a reprex.

00:25:10.500 --> 00:25:18.680
But somehow the discipline of knowing that you're preparing something to show other people

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:22.140
makes you, like, get your ducks in a row.

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:26.219
And it also consistently forces you to minimize things.

00:25:26.219 --> 00:25:28.219
And a lot of people, the numbers vary.

00:25:28.219 --> 00:25:30.099
I obviously made these up.

00:25:30.099 --> 00:25:34.060
But a lot of people report that when they finally decide that they're going to post

00:25:34.060 --> 00:25:40.180
something on GitHub or Stack Overflow or RStudio's community site, 80 to 90% of the

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:43.619
time they solve their own problem.

00:25:43.619 --> 00:25:47.800
Because it just got them working in a productive way.

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:50.079
And that won't happen every time.

00:25:50.079 --> 00:25:54.420
And so when it doesn't happen, it still means that you have this beautiful version of your

00:25:54.420 --> 00:25:59.300
pain that you can post somewhere in a way that other people are more likely to engage

00:25:59.300 --> 00:26:00.939
with it.

00:26:00.939 --> 00:26:02.739
Okay.

00:26:02.739 --> 00:26:06.339
We're going to move on in some sense to the heart of the talk, maybe what you thought

00:26:06.339 --> 00:26:09.739
it would be, which is about proper debugging.

00:26:09.739 --> 00:26:13.300
But I do want to say I think the two previous things are actually incredibly important.

00:26:13.300 --> 00:26:17.540
They don't feel like rocket science, but they can prevent you from getting to this point

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:18.819
a lot.

00:26:18.819 --> 00:26:22.579
But so what if you haven't solved your own problem and no one stepped forward to solve

00:26:22.579 --> 00:26:23.900
it for you?

00:26:23.900 --> 00:26:28.579
You have no choice but to debug it yourself.

00:26:28.579 --> 00:26:36.540
So I'm opening another poll that might be a little bit mysterious to some of you.

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:38.219
And we'll talk about this again at the end.

00:26:38.219 --> 00:26:39.739
So this will be open for a while.

00:26:39.739 --> 00:26:45.819
So I want to know if you have ever gotten stuck in R's debugger.

00:26:45.819 --> 00:26:48.739
And answer this at will.

00:26:48.739 --> 00:26:55.020
So this mood I want to set here is that this is a pretty famous far side cartoon about

00:26:55.020 --> 00:27:01.219
how we talk to our dogs, where we express all these detailed emotions or detailed instructions

00:27:01.219 --> 00:27:07.180
and we're pretty sure that all the dog hears is blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah,

00:27:07.180 --> 00:27:09.140
blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:27:09.140 --> 00:27:15.219
And I think a lot of us process error messages this way.

00:27:15.219 --> 00:27:20.180
So this is a real error message.

00:27:20.180 --> 00:27:24.420
It's going to strike fear in the hearts of those of you who can actually read it.

00:27:24.819 --> 00:27:29.060
It's the classic can't install R Java error message.

00:27:29.060 --> 00:27:35.619
And instead of reading all of this detailed information that might help you sort out exactly

00:27:35.619 --> 00:27:46.140
what went wrong, I think a lot of us just see error, no, failed, and go back into this

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:49.780
speculate, dither, and fret cycle.

00:27:49.780 --> 00:27:54.540
So these proper debugging tools are nerdy and they're technical and you're going to

00:27:54.540 --> 00:28:01.020
have to push through big, ugly error messages or call stacks, but you can do it.

00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:06.540
So I'm going to show you a small example in this section of a function I've written called

00:28:06.540 --> 00:28:08.979
fruit average.

00:28:08.979 --> 00:28:14.140
So the type of input that it takes is a data frame where we have one column for each piece

00:28:14.140 --> 00:28:18.219
of fruit and one row for different fruit attributes.

00:28:18.219 --> 00:28:24.660
So we know that a blackberry has four calories, weighs nine grams, and my personal rating

00:28:24.660 --> 00:28:27.420
on yumminess is six.

00:28:27.420 --> 00:28:33.699
And so when you pass that object to fruit average and give it a pattern, it will find

00:28:33.699 --> 00:28:39.260
the matching columns and average their attributes.

00:28:39.260 --> 00:28:42.540
So that's what it looks like when we're averaging two fruits.

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:44.859
What if I ask for melon?

00:28:44.859 --> 00:28:48.099
Melon isn't in this data set, so I get no fruits.

00:28:48.099 --> 00:28:53.260
You could argue that found zero fruits, like, pluralization is really hard.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:55.819
I didn't get to spend a lot of time on this, so that's fine.

00:28:55.819 --> 00:29:00.819
It's not beautiful, but it's fine for an early edge case.

00:29:00.819 --> 00:29:02.140
But here's a problem.

00:29:02.140 --> 00:29:06.260
So if I ask for the fruits whose name contain black, I thought maybe there would be more

00:29:06.260 --> 00:29:07.260
than one.

00:29:07.260 --> 00:29:10.579
Blackberry, blackcurrant.

00:29:10.579 --> 00:29:16.579
I get a weird message, like, found fruits, and then I get an error.

00:29:16.579 --> 00:29:22.500
The error is about row means being applied to minidat, and I'm being told that X must

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:23.500
be an array.

00:29:23.500 --> 00:29:26.140
So I didn't call row means.

00:29:26.140 --> 00:29:29.979
I didn't make minidat, and I don't know who X is.

00:29:29.979 --> 00:29:36.060
And so this is a common sort of confusion situation where you are going to have to slowly

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:38.140
figure out what all of those mean.

00:29:38.140 --> 00:29:41.540
You're going to fiddle around in the bowels of fruit average to figure out what's going

00:29:41.540 --> 00:29:48.979
on, and does fruit average contain a bug, or did you somehow send unexpected data?

00:29:48.979 --> 00:29:54.739
So when I thought about this part of the talk, which is kind of hard to deliver in this setting,

00:29:54.739 --> 00:30:03.060
because you can't all do exercises and whatnot, I decided to take a tour through three modes

00:30:03.060 --> 00:30:06.140
of true R debugging, and I'm using a death metaphor.

00:30:06.140 --> 00:30:11.140
I think it's accurate, because we are talking about fatal errors.

00:30:11.140 --> 00:30:15.260
So we're going to go through some things from the left side to the right, and they're

00:30:15.260 --> 00:30:21.780
basically in order of probably what you should try, and also in order of how much control

00:30:21.780 --> 00:30:23.540
you have.

00:30:23.540 --> 00:30:27.619
So the least amount of control is the death certificate, where you can just learn a few

00:30:27.619 --> 00:30:29.819
basic facts.

00:30:29.819 --> 00:30:35.099
The next level up is you get to participate in an autopsy, and you are actually allowed

00:30:35.099 --> 00:30:37.300
to examine the subject.

00:30:37.300 --> 00:30:43.699
And then finally, if you haven't watched Game of Thrones, this creature is reanimating a

00:30:43.699 --> 00:30:50.780
lot of dead people to create an army, but the idea is of reanimation or resuscitation.

00:30:50.780 --> 00:30:57.500
So this is how I map these on to some classic R debugging strategies, and we're going to

00:30:57.500 --> 00:30:59.540
go through them in this order.

00:30:59.540 --> 00:31:07.420
So traceback is your first line of defense, I guess, where you can see what all was called

00:31:07.420 --> 00:31:08.540
on the way to death.

00:31:08.540 --> 00:31:14.739
So it is very much like a death certificate, where you get some rather spare facts.

00:31:14.739 --> 00:31:19.180
If that doesn't allow you to solve your problem, you might go a little bit more interventional,

00:31:19.180 --> 00:31:25.819
and you can change the error option in R so that right before the function exits, like

00:31:25.819 --> 00:31:33.180
still on a one-way ticket out, you can do an autopsy and inspect the call stack, but

00:31:33.180 --> 00:31:41.180
you can't really change the past at this point, whereas if you use browser and related techniques,

00:31:41.180 --> 00:31:47.380
you actually interrupt things before death is inevitable and get a much better opportunity

00:31:47.380 --> 00:31:51.140
to maybe fix things, so we're going to go through these.

00:31:51.140 --> 00:31:56.900
So if I call fruit average on our troublesome example, I get the error, you immediately

00:31:56.900 --> 00:32:01.739
would call traceback here, and what you do is you read this from the bottom up, and it

00:32:01.739 --> 00:32:08.099
shows you the sequence of calls that led to the error, so you called fruit average, apparently

00:32:08.099 --> 00:32:13.780
somewhere inside fruit average on line 5, in fact, romeans got called, and somewhere

00:32:13.780 --> 00:32:16.819
inside romeans, there was a stop.

00:32:16.819 --> 00:32:22.859
So this is called the call stack, and that's a term that applies across many, many languages

00:32:22.859 --> 00:32:28.459
in R, we summon it with the function traceback.

00:32:28.459 --> 00:32:32.579
So when I decided to do this topic, I thought, I am finally going to get to the bottom of

00:32:32.579 --> 00:32:39.780
what all those different terms mean, and it turns out that you can take any two of those

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:46.619
words and you can probably put them in any order, and you will find some pocket of the

00:32:46.619 --> 00:32:52.859
R community who uses that term, except callback, which is real and is totally different, but

00:32:52.859 --> 00:32:56.380
you hear people talk about the call stack, the traceback, the stack trace, and the back

00:32:56.380 --> 00:33:00.859
trace all the time, and they all mean the same thing.

00:33:00.859 --> 00:33:10.020
An alternative view that's coming for back traces is from Arlang, so Arlang is accumulating

00:33:10.020 --> 00:33:16.380
more and more functionality for developers, really, for throwing class errors, but one

00:33:16.380 --> 00:33:23.939
of the things it also offers is some new takes at how to present the call stack, and that's

00:33:23.939 --> 00:33:29.219
the one part of that area of Arlang that might be relevant to just about anyone, mostly this

00:33:29.219 --> 00:33:35.260
is developer-facing, but this is an alternative view of that same call stack, and it's in

00:33:35.260 --> 00:33:40.660
a different order, and there's some nice nesting, and so this is being designed with readability

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:45.540
in mind, so if you like looking at call stacks this way, there's something you can do in

00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:48.300
your startup file.

00:33:48.300 --> 00:33:54.060
And if you like using RStudio, it also has a really nice default method for how to handle

00:33:54.060 --> 00:34:00.619
errors, and it will by default show you the base R traceback and also offer you an easy

00:34:00.619 --> 00:34:03.939
way to get to some of the techniques that are coming next.

00:34:03.939 --> 00:34:06.459
So that's traceback.

00:34:06.459 --> 00:34:13.139
So the last two techniques I want to talk about are the ones where you get to intervene.

00:34:13.139 --> 00:34:21.179
Either intervene post-death in the autopsy or intervene even earlier, and this is just

00:34:21.179 --> 00:34:26.020
a little video that I think totally evokes what's going on and how it feels that you

00:34:26.020 --> 00:34:35.219
get to open this hidden door and go into this whole world that has a microwave and a refrigerator,

00:34:35.219 --> 00:34:39.939
and you can certainly look at things and you might be able to do things in there.

00:34:39.939 --> 00:34:42.179
That's how it feels to be in the debugger.

00:34:42.179 --> 00:34:44.979
It's less charming, I have to say.

00:34:44.979 --> 00:34:49.500
And then you come back out, close the door, and hopefully that hidden world goes back

00:34:49.500 --> 00:34:50.500
to being hidden.

00:34:50.500 --> 00:34:54.860
But that's kind of what's going on in these next two techniques.

00:34:54.860 --> 00:35:00.659
So if you decide that you actually need to see the state of things at the time of an

00:35:00.659 --> 00:35:04.699
error, you can set your error option to the recover function.

00:35:04.699 --> 00:35:11.179
So right as you're on your way out the door, execution will pause, and you're allowed to

00:35:11.179 --> 00:35:18.219
look at frames, and those are the environments corresponding to the different function calls.

00:35:18.219 --> 00:35:20.139
So I'm going to pick one here.

00:35:20.139 --> 00:35:24.459
I want to see what minidat is, okay?

00:35:24.459 --> 00:35:32.379
So we're in the usual interactive R console, but you know things are special because the

00:35:32.379 --> 00:35:38.540
prompt contains the word browse, and one which tells us which frame we're in, and you can

00:35:38.540 --> 00:35:46.020
print objects here, but a lot of what people do here is they use LS to see which objects

00:35:46.020 --> 00:35:53.739
exist or in this case I'm using LS.stir to look at each object in the environment, and

00:35:53.739 --> 00:35:59.860
I am particularly interested in minidat because I know it's my nemesis and I notice that it's

00:35:59.860 --> 00:36:04.379
an integer vector, and I know from the error that it's being sent to romains, which I'm

00:36:04.379 --> 00:36:06.899
pretty sure needs a two-dimensional object.

00:36:06.899 --> 00:36:11.179
So I think many of you, your spidey sense is already telling you what the problem might

00:36:11.179 --> 00:36:12.780
be here.

00:36:12.780 --> 00:36:18.219
If you do this recover work inside our studio, it's great because your usual environment

00:36:18.219 --> 00:36:24.659
pane is brought to bear on this problem, and you can be looking at the execution environments

00:36:24.659 --> 00:36:30.219
of those functions in the normal beautiful environment viewer.

00:36:30.219 --> 00:36:33.139
But let's say so now I have a theory about what's wrong.

00:36:33.139 --> 00:36:37.540
I think the fact that this somehow became a vector is my problem.

00:36:37.540 --> 00:36:40.340
But now I want to sort of test that.

00:36:40.340 --> 00:36:45.300
So the final most interventional thing you can possibly do is we're going to use browser,

00:36:45.300 --> 00:36:51.739
and so this last debugging mode is most powerful if you actually have the source of the function

00:36:51.739 --> 00:36:53.100
you're trying to work with.

00:36:53.100 --> 00:36:57.219
There are ways to get here without that, but it works best when you do because you'll have

00:36:57.219 --> 00:37:00.219
something called source references.

00:37:00.219 --> 00:37:03.979
So that was the first look you got at the actual source of fruit average, and what I

00:37:03.979 --> 00:37:10.939
do is I insert a call to the browser function in the body of the function, and you want

00:37:10.939 --> 00:37:15.459
to insert it before the error, and if you knew where the error was, we wouldn't be having

00:37:15.459 --> 00:37:22.020
this conversation, so you often want to start high and then you can work it lower as you

00:37:22.020 --> 00:37:26.679
learn more about the problem, so I'm putting it as the first line.

00:37:26.679 --> 00:37:32.020
And there are, as I said, other ways to get into a similar world that I simply don't have

00:37:32.020 --> 00:37:39.580
time to cover, so in the iStudio IDE, again, if you've got the source open, you can set

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:44.379
what's called an IDE break point, and that's what that red dot means, and then you're not

00:37:44.379 --> 00:37:50.699
editing your code, so a lot of people find that a nicer workflow, and if you don't have

00:37:50.699 --> 00:37:55.699
the source to a function, maybe it's in a package owned by someone else and you haven't

00:37:55.699 --> 00:38:01.139
bothered to download the source, or it's base R, you can use debug to get a fairly

00:38:01.139 --> 00:38:05.979
similar experience, but it's a little more hampered by the fact that you don't have the

00:38:05.979 --> 00:38:07.379
actual source.

00:38:07.379 --> 00:38:08.379
Okay.

00:38:08.379 --> 00:38:14.939
So this is a little video of me live browsing this problem.

00:38:14.939 --> 00:38:20.620
So first thing I do is I source a version of fruit average that has that browser call

00:38:20.620 --> 00:38:22.419
in it.

00:38:22.419 --> 00:38:27.419
Then I'm going to immediately call it on my usual troublesome example, and what you're

00:38:27.419 --> 00:38:34.020
going to see is I immediately get kicked into this slightly different version of the regular

00:38:34.020 --> 00:38:38.979
interactive, our console and the browse thing will be in the prompt.

00:38:38.979 --> 00:38:45.179
So I can use N now to go next line, next line, and I'm walking through that function.

00:38:45.179 --> 00:38:48.239
It might be someone else's function, line by line.

00:38:48.239 --> 00:38:50.879
And finally we get to minidat.

00:38:50.879 --> 00:38:56.439
So I'm going to inspect minidat very exhaustively and see what it looks like.

00:38:56.439 --> 00:39:01.239
I'm going to see what its dimensions are, which are null, because it's a vector, and

00:39:01.239 --> 00:39:06.239
how many columns it has, which is also null, because it's a vector, and I'm pretty sure

00:39:06.239 --> 00:39:11.879
this is my problem, but here's the cool thing that you can't do in any other debugging mode

00:39:11.879 --> 00:39:19.360
is I can redefine minidat and I'm going to do the same subsetting, but I'm going to specify

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:24.959
drop equals false, so that even if I get just one column, it's still going to be a two-dimensional

00:39:24.959 --> 00:39:25.959
object.

00:39:25.959 --> 00:39:28.360
I check the dimensions again.

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:34.040
And then I can resume execution, and I'm going to get the error of the message I should see

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:40.040
and I'm going to get the result I should see, and so this is how you sort of test a theory

00:39:40.239 --> 00:39:44.840
or pilot a solution to what you think might be going wrong.

00:39:44.840 --> 00:39:50.959
So that's what using browser and there's different ways to get into this world looks like.

00:39:50.959 --> 00:39:57.199
So to conclude this section, every time I've talked about this before, people come up to

00:39:57.199 --> 00:40:00.760
me afterwards to talk about this, they're like it must be in the talk, it has to be

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:01.959
in the talk.

00:40:01.959 --> 00:40:06.000
So it's very easy, and I certainly have experienced this myself, to be in the browser, you think

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:09.639
you're really clever, I'm going to upgrade my debugging skills, and you don't know how

00:40:09.639 --> 00:40:11.679
to get back out of it.

00:40:11.679 --> 00:40:16.600
So you will never remember this, but it's capital Q, okay?

00:40:16.600 --> 00:40:21.879
If you're in RStudio, there's also a helpful button, a stop button with a square that will

00:40:21.879 --> 00:40:23.800
get you out of it.

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:25.760
You'll eventually learn.

00:40:25.760 --> 00:40:30.879
And then two things that are more proactive to know about is if you've used debug on a

00:40:30.879 --> 00:40:38.760
function, it means every time you execute, you're going to get kicked back into the browser.

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:42.959
Debug on the same function is how you cancel this behavior.

00:40:42.959 --> 00:40:47.120
And some people have been burned by this so badly so many times that they have a policy

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:52.679
of only using debug once, and what it does is it will send you into this environment

00:40:52.679 --> 00:40:59.280
browser exactly once, the first time you hit that point, and then never again.

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:02.040
So it's sort of self-destructing.

00:41:02.040 --> 00:41:04.959
So those are all good to know about.

00:41:04.959 --> 00:41:10.919
Our last section is more future-facing, and it's how do you create your projects in a

00:41:10.919 --> 00:41:16.320
way that they are less hospitable to bugs, and when things go wrong, because of course

00:41:16.320 --> 00:41:22.199
they're going to, you're giving yourself more information to help you solve it.

00:41:22.199 --> 00:41:27.439
So if you fixed something once or you've seen some weird edge behavior that causes all hell

00:41:27.439 --> 00:41:32.479
to break loose, do something to make sure that that stays fixed.

00:41:32.479 --> 00:41:36.919
And these tips are increasingly going to be more package development focused, although

00:41:36.919 --> 00:41:39.479
some of it is relevant to scripts.

00:41:39.479 --> 00:41:44.719
But so based on the example we just worked, like if fruit average was in a package I maintain,

00:41:44.719 --> 00:41:51.760
once I make that fix, drop equals false, I also add this test to make sure that the behavior

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:58.439
is what it should be when we have zero fruits, one fruit, and two fruits matching.

00:41:58.439 --> 00:42:04.959
And so for people working with data analysis in a data script, this is another hypothetical,

00:42:04.959 --> 00:42:10.000
like let's imagine you're importing fruit data on a regular basis, and somewhere down

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:15.360
in the pipeline there's an implicit assumption that everything's numeric, and maybe you've

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:20.739
been burned by having things unexpectedly import as character.

00:42:20.739 --> 00:42:26.360
Once you've spent a half day debugging that, you should add an assertion in your pipeline

00:42:26.479 --> 00:42:30.360
so that the next time that happens, because you probably can't prevent it, you at least

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:35.840
know very early and you have a really excellent error message for yourself.

00:42:35.840 --> 00:42:40.399
So over time you're going to accumulate lots of these sorts of checks on whether you make

00:42:40.399 --> 00:42:47.639
a data pipeline or on a package, and so you want to be running them en masse and really

00:42:47.639 --> 00:42:49.000
often.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:53.159
So two great big collections of checks that you could be running, and this is definitely

00:42:53.159 --> 00:42:59.840
about packages now, is our command check itself will show you if your package is meeting

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:06.040
all the various criteria enforced by CRAN, and for the vast majority of those, it's a

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:10.100
standard you want to meet, whether you're going to put your package on CRAN or not,

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:14.620
and something you'd want to run really often, and then you're going to have custom tests

00:43:14.620 --> 00:43:19.639
like the one I just showed you that uniquely test the functionality of your work, so our

00:43:19.639 --> 00:43:25.479
group uses a package called test that to express those and to sort of choreograph the

00:43:25.479 --> 00:43:30.439
running of them, and when you set that up, you can run just them, and then it's also

00:43:30.439 --> 00:43:35.919
wired up that those will run every time our command check done, and this means you're

00:43:35.919 --> 00:43:42.879
much more likely to run all of your tests, and the sooner you learn that you broke something,

00:43:42.879 --> 00:43:48.280
the easier it is to fix it, because usually the delta is smaller and you're looking in

00:43:48.280 --> 00:43:50.300
a smaller haystack.

00:43:50.300 --> 00:43:56.040
If you only run our command check every ten months, you've made a very big haystack to

00:43:56.040 --> 00:44:03.000
look through, and then the next level up is to run those checks not on your machine, but

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:09.000
on their machine, and that pretty much means that you have to be using a whole other set

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:14.399
of practices that are beyond this talk, but that you are keeping your code under version

00:44:14.399 --> 00:44:22.760
control, pushing it to a remote version control host like a GitHub or a GitLab or a Bitbucket,

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:27.000
and you'll use something called continuous integration, and every time you make a change,

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:33.300
it will kick off running our command check, which includes your test, preferably over

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:38.760
many different operating systems, so you get extra credit here if you are running it on

00:44:38.760 --> 00:44:45.159
different operating systems, and, again, this just means that you find errors sooner

00:44:45.159 --> 00:44:48.159
when they're easier to fix.

00:44:48.159 --> 00:44:56.399
This last this particular point is extremely personal, so I have found that there are certain

00:44:56.399 --> 00:45:04.919
patterns I will use inside a function or certain data structures that later prove to be very

00:45:04.919 --> 00:45:12.159
enriched for bugs, they're like bug magnets, and when I have to go back in and tinker with

00:45:12.159 --> 00:45:22.320
that piece of code, I hate it, so for me, it's recursion and high-dimensional data arrays,

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:25.159
like big dimensional data cubes, okay?

00:45:25.159 --> 00:45:29.560
So if you need that abstraction to solve your problem, absolutely, of course, you should

00:45:29.560 --> 00:45:37.800
leave it in, but if I'm honest with myself, sometimes I did this because I could.

00:45:37.800 --> 00:45:42.520
And both of these things I find make perfect sense when you've been thinking about nothing

00:45:42.520 --> 00:45:47.800
but that problem for three days, and it's just so elegant, and then you go away and

00:45:47.800 --> 00:45:50.879
six months later, this is where the bug will be.

00:45:50.879 --> 00:45:53.000
It is not so elegant anymore.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:58.600
It takes a long time to, like, upload all of that back into your RAM.

00:45:58.600 --> 00:46:03.159
And so I find that if you have some pattern like that where you kick yourself for using

00:46:03.159 --> 00:46:08.840
it when you could have done something simpler, stop doing that.

00:46:08.840 --> 00:46:15.959
Here's a Douglas Adam quote that I think has a lot of relevance to building data packages.

00:46:15.959 --> 00:46:21.080
The major difference between a thing that might go wrong and a thing that cannot possibly

00:46:21.080 --> 00:46:27.000
go wrong is that when the thing that cannot possibly goes wrong, it's impossible to get

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:29.040
that and repair.

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:33.679
And so the idea I want to talk about here is that as you're building things, you will

00:46:33.679 --> 00:46:40.679
be so happy later if you've left yourself some kind of an access panel.

00:46:40.679 --> 00:46:44.439
And in this case, you know, there's a valve here that you can go in and turn off or up

00:46:44.439 --> 00:46:45.439
or down.

00:46:45.439 --> 00:46:49.280
And I'm not going to go through all of the examples here, but I'm going through several

00:46:49.280 --> 00:46:54.719
packages near and dear to me, and I'm also showing an example from Base R where if you're

00:46:54.719 --> 00:47:03.639
trying to debug Excel import or making HTTP calls or some sort of hairy nonstandard evaluation

00:47:03.639 --> 00:47:11.479
problem, you have a way to flip a switch and suddenly be getting a lot more information.

00:47:11.479 --> 00:47:13.800
And this is great for package developers.

00:47:13.800 --> 00:47:15.959
It's very useful during development.

00:47:15.959 --> 00:47:21.040
And then also when you're trying to help a user debug something and you're having that

00:47:21.040 --> 00:47:29.040
sort of vocabulary communication problem, you can ask them, open the access panel.

00:47:29.040 --> 00:47:34.340
Run your problem and send you a lot more information that might help you get unstuck.

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:38.320
My last point is about writing error messages.

00:47:38.320 --> 00:47:45.560
So we've come back to where we started, which is with the world or the R's most famous error

00:47:45.560 --> 00:47:48.520
message, object of type closure is not subsettable.

00:47:48.520 --> 00:47:54.580
My theory is that the reason this sends people for such a loop is the word closure.

00:47:54.580 --> 00:47:56.719
And that a lot of people don't know what that means.

00:47:56.719 --> 00:48:02.080
So we could also in most cases use the word function there.

00:48:02.080 --> 00:48:06.320
I'm not sure if that would immediately make everyone love this error message, like I totally

00:48:06.320 --> 00:48:08.879
know what to do now, I can fix my problem.

00:48:08.879 --> 00:48:14.719
But I think it removes one communication barrier.

00:48:14.719 --> 00:48:21.520
In the tidyverse, we've been trying to create some sort of standard for ourselves for error

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:26.479
messages, where we return as much information as we have.

00:48:26.479 --> 00:48:31.959
Like where the error occurred, the name of the object involved, if we're pretty sure

00:48:31.959 --> 00:48:35.439
we have that right, and maybe even a hint.

00:48:35.439 --> 00:48:43.479
So this is a much more controversial version of object of closure is not subsettable, where

00:48:43.479 --> 00:48:47.679
we say I can't subset a function for you.

00:48:47.679 --> 00:48:50.320
Have you forgotten to define a variable named df?

00:48:50.320 --> 00:48:53.719
So this is the type of hint we give sometimes.

00:48:53.719 --> 00:48:56.159
It's extremely dangerous, though.

00:48:56.159 --> 00:48:58.919
Because people really trust you.

00:48:58.919 --> 00:49:03.719
And if you're wrong, it's really difficult to predict all the different ways people can

00:49:03.719 --> 00:49:05.040
get an error message.

00:49:05.040 --> 00:49:08.639
If you're wrong, you're going to send a lot of people on a wild goose chase.

00:49:08.639 --> 00:49:14.320
So I'm not sure that this error is really amenable to this, but a much cleaner example

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:16.080
is from dplyr.

00:49:16.080 --> 00:49:22.439
So dplyr has a function called filter, where you can ask for just certain rows in a dataset.

00:49:22.439 --> 00:49:27.239
And it's very easy to use the single equal sign when you want the logical double equal

00:49:27.239 --> 00:49:28.520
sign.

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:34.120
And apparently enough people have fallen down this pothole that the dplyr maintainers have

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:40.159
had mercy on all of us, and it's pretty clear what people mean to suggest maybe you need

00:49:40.159 --> 00:49:42.280
to be using the double equal sign.

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:46.800
So I think of all the error messages that have hints, this is my favorite, and it's

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:51.439
the one that has helped me the most.

00:49:51.439 --> 00:49:52.719
So that brings us to the end here.

00:49:52.719 --> 00:49:57.399
I'm going to review your troubleshooting blueprint, okay?

00:49:57.399 --> 00:49:58.840
So something weird happens.

00:49:58.840 --> 00:50:03.399
I think the very first thing you should do is turn it off and turn it on again.

00:50:03.399 --> 00:50:07.280
You'll be amazed how often your problem is gone.

00:50:07.280 --> 00:50:11.439
If it's not gone, try to make a reprex.

00:50:11.439 --> 00:50:15.679
Pretend like you're going to send it out into the world and you need to minimize it, you

00:50:15.679 --> 00:50:18.760
need to write a clean, self-contained version.

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:25.800
Again, you will be amazed how often that process gets you unstuck and leads to a productive

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:27.719
solution.

00:50:27.719 --> 00:50:31.479
If that doesn't work, you will have to dig into the error.

00:50:31.479 --> 00:50:37.939
And I really think using the proper debugging tools is very useful, and I know that I put

00:50:37.939 --> 00:50:41.040
off that day way too long.

00:50:41.040 --> 00:50:46.919
So if they look kind of intimidating, I suggest that you time box it.

00:50:46.919 --> 00:50:51.879
So maybe say the next time I come up with one of these weird situations, I'm going to

00:50:51.879 --> 00:50:58.399
fiddle around with these traceback, recover, and browser for ten minutes.

00:50:58.399 --> 00:51:02.479
And if I haven't really gotten anywhere, I have permission to quit and go back to my

00:51:02.479 --> 00:51:03.840
old ways.

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:07.919
And I think you'll find that with just a little bit of usage, you get a lot better much more

00:51:07.919 --> 00:51:09.159
quickly.

00:51:09.159 --> 00:51:11.719
And then finally, plan for the unexpected.

00:51:11.719 --> 00:51:16.040
So you are clearly going to be debugging everything you build.

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:18.320
I'm sorry to tell you that.

00:51:18.320 --> 00:51:24.639
And so you might as well build it in such a way that when it fails, it fails informatively.

00:51:24.639 --> 00:51:27.560
When you break things, you learn quickly.

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:32.879
And again, just make it easier to recover from the bugs that will inevitably come up.

00:51:32.879 --> 00:51:37.719
So there's the short link again if you want to see more links about the talk, get the

00:51:37.719 --> 00:51:38.719
slides.

00:51:38.719 --> 00:51:43.080
They're kind of large, so I would recommend that you look at them on speaker deck.

00:51:43.080 --> 00:51:47.199
But I really want to give big thanks to two people, virtual people.

00:51:47.199 --> 00:51:52.879
First, the Tidyverse team has listened to me practice parts of this talk for many, many

00:51:52.879 --> 00:51:54.280
months.

00:51:54.919 --> 00:52:00.239
And I have to say that we actually learned a lot about debugging from each other based

00:52:00.239 --> 00:52:05.199
on these every sort of two or three week conversations.

00:52:05.199 --> 00:52:10.840
And part of why I want to say that is a lot of this stuff maybe feels a bit exotic, especially

00:52:10.840 --> 00:52:12.639
the debugging section.

00:52:12.639 --> 00:52:17.919
And just let it be known that people on the Tidyverse team learned things by talking to

00:52:17.919 --> 00:52:19.439
each other about this.

00:52:19.439 --> 00:52:21.719
Not everything we talked about makes it into the talk.

00:52:21.719 --> 00:52:22.719
It's more technical.

00:52:22.719 --> 00:52:28.280
But people don't talk about this enough, I've decided, and people have cool tricks to share

